  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Peace &amp; Development Programme (PDP): Market Opportunities in the Somali Region of Ethiopia (MORE)</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="1">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">A market systems development (MSD) approach is at the core of the MORE design. We will work with key government agencies, private sector actors and community organisations to address underlying systemic constraints and catalyse changes to institutions and market structures that are sustainable. MORE will also mainstream a context sensitive approach into all decision-making and activity implementation, ensuring effective stakeholder coordination and communication and rigorous application of the Do No Harm methodology. MORE will ensure active community engagement, as we believe that communities are the most effective agents for their own transformation, and close partnership with government will also be essential for successful implementation and sustainability. MORE will focus on innovation and learning, to adjust to the dynamic context through ongoing learning and feedback. While working with a diverse range of actors, we will maintain a clear focus on vulnerable households and individuals that are the primary target beneficiaries, particularly women and youth. MC will work with ACPA, ESDA and LTS to maximise impact, drawing on each consortium member&apos;s expertise and skill.;</narrative>
  </description>
  <description type="2">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">The proposed Market Opportunities in the Somali Region of Ethiopia (MORE) programme will transform the lives of 125,000 vulnerable TOP households in the Somali Regional State of Ethiopia through sustainable employment and business generation activities.
The programme will address the three major constraints faced by TOP households in accessing alternative livelihoods: limited business and livelihood opportunities caused by undeveloped and fragmented markets
(addressed through Output 1); widespread lack of access to financial services (Output 3); and lack of marketable skills (Output 4). Output 2 addresses the particular challenges faced by rural TOP households in terms of vulnerability to shocks, diminishing assets and lack of access to services and alternative livelihood opportunities.

Output 1. Increased participation by TOP households in at least 10 agricultural and non-agricultural markets, resulting in increased income
Output 2. Increased participation in VSLAs by rural TOP households resulting in growth in household livelihood assets
Output 3. Improved access to financial services for TOP households and other market actors
Output 4. A dynamic &apos;employment and business support services sector providing effective services to increased numbers of TOP households

;</narrative>
  </description>
